</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Serrated polyps are a recently recognized family of colonic polyps with subgroups that harbor future malignant potential. In the past, the significance of these lesions to the colorectal cancer carcinogenesis pathway was not recognized nor well understood. It is now known that serrated polyps account for approximately one-fourth of all sporadic colorectal cancers. The sessile serrated polyp (SSP) (also known as a sessile serrated adenoma [SSA]) is the main lesion of interest given its prevalence and subtle presentation. These lesions are often flat—only minimally raised from the colonic surface—and occur in the right colon. These lesions have been a likely common cause of screening failure at colonoscopy, although detection has improved with improved recognition over time. Although detection is difficult with image-based screening, serrated lesions can be detected at CT colonography. The prevalence in CT colonography screening populations mirrors the rates at colonoscopy for similar size categories. CT colonography allows identification of SSPs despite their minimally raised profile owing to the phenomenon of lesional contrast material coating. This contrast material coat aids in lesion detection by highlighting the subtle morphologic changes as well as increasing confidence that a true lesion exists despite a flat morphology. It is important to optimize contrast material coating with specific bowel preparations and other technical parameters. Radiologists should be aware of these technical and interpretation issues. Armed with this knowledge, radiologists should expect excellent results in detection of these subtle but important lesions.</div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2017</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2018170110">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2018170110">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170110/asset/images/large/rg.2018170110.fig1.jpeg" height="2246" width="3000" aria-labelledby="fig1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span>. Colorectal carcinogenesis. Diagram shows the two histologic lines that can turn into cancer. The majority of sporadic cancers occur via an adenomatous pathway. Screening with removal of the polyp precursor represents true prevention (and conveys the most benefit), whereas screening during the asymptomatic phase with removal of an early cancer improves rates of cure.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170110&amp;id=fig1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170110/asset/images/large/rg.2018170110.fig2a.jpeg" height="1141" width="1340" aria-labelledby="fig2a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span>. Appearance of SSP at colonoscopy. <b>(a)</b> Optical colonoscopic image shows the typical flat subtle appearance of an SSP (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> Optical colonoscopic image in another patient shows the overlying adherent yellowish mucin that is often used to help detect flat SSPs at colonoscopy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170110&amp;id=fig2a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170110/asset/images/large/rg.2018170110.fig2b.jpeg" height="1141" width="1314" aria-labelledby="fig2b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span>. Appearance of SSP at colonoscopy. <b>(a)</b> Optical colonoscopic image shows the typical flat subtle appearance of an SSP (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> Optical colonoscopic image in another patient shows the overlying adherent yellowish mucin that is often used to help detect flat SSPs at colonoscopy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170110&amp;id=fig2b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170110/asset/images/large/rg.2018170110.fig3a.jpeg" height="1315" width="1678" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span>. Lesional contrast material coat of SSP at screening CT colonography. <b>(a, b)</b> Supine <b>(a)</b> and prone <b>(b)</b> axial two-dimensional (2D) CT colonography images show adherent contrast material (arrowheads), which aids in detection. Note how the contrast material outlines the lesion but not the normal colonic mucosa (magnified inset). <b>(c)</b> Three-dimensional (3D) endoluminal view shows that this flat lesion is more obvious and appears sessile, as the reconstruction is a combination of the polyp and the contrast material, while the colonoscopic image (inset) shows the lesion's true flat nature (arrowhead). <b>(d)</b> Axial 2D CT colonography image in another patient shows a polyp without a contrast material coat (arrowhead), which is much more difficult to see and is characterized by a subtle undulation. <b>(e)</b> Sagittal 2D reconstruction better shows the lesion (arrowhead). <b>(f)</b> Colonoscopic image confirms the lesion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170110&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170110/asset/images/large/rg.2018170110.fig3b.jpeg" height="1315" width="1668" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span>. Lesional contrast material coat of SSP at screening CT colonography. <b>(a, b)</b> Supine <b>(a)</b> and prone <b>(b)</b> axial two-dimensional (2D) CT colonography images show adherent contrast material (arrowheads), which aids in detection. Note how the contrast material outlines the lesion but not the normal colonic mucosa (magnified inset). <b>(c)</b> Three-dimensional (3D) endoluminal view shows that this flat lesion is more obvious and appears sessile, as the reconstruction is a combination of the polyp and the contrast material, while the colonoscopic image (inset) shows the lesion's true flat nature (arrowhead). <b>(d)</b> Axial 2D CT colonography image in another patient shows a polyp without a contrast material coat (arrowhead), which is much more difficult to see and is characterized by a subtle undulation. <b>(e)</b> Sagittal 2D reconstruction better shows the lesion (arrowhead). <b>(f)</b> Colonoscopic image confirms the lesion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170110&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170110/asset/images/large/rg.2018170110.fig3c.jpeg" height="1503" width="1514" aria-labelledby="fig3c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3c</span>. Lesional contrast material coat of SSP at screening CT colonography. <b>(a, b)</b> Supine <b>(a)</b> and prone <b>(b)</b> axial two-dimensional (2D) CT colonography images show adherent contrast material (arrowheads), which aids in detection. Note how the contrast material outlines the lesion but not the normal colonic mucosa (magnified inset). <b>(c)</b> Three-dimensional (3D) endoluminal view shows that this flat lesion is more obvious and appears sessile, as the reconstruction is a combination of the polyp and the contrast material, while the colonoscopic image (inset) shows the lesion's true flat nature (arrowhead). <b>(d)</b> Axial 2D CT colonography image in another patient shows a polyp without a contrast material coat (arrowhead), which is much more difficult to see and is characterized by a subtle undulation. <b>(e)</b> Sagittal 2D reconstruction better shows the lesion (arrowhead). <b>(f)</b> Colonoscopic image confirms the lesion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170110&amp;id=fig3c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170110/asset/images/large/rg.2018170110.fig3d.jpeg" height="1503" width="1836" aria-labelledby="fig3d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3d</span>. Lesional contrast material coat of SSP at screening CT colonography. <b>(a, b)</b> Supine <b>(a)</b> and prone <b>(b)</b> axial two-dimensional (2D) CT colonography images show adherent contrast material (arrowheads), which aids in detection. Note how the contrast material outlines the lesion but not the normal colonic mucosa (magnified inset). <b>(c)</b> Three-dimensional (3D) endoluminal view shows that this flat lesion is more obvious and appears sessile, as the reconstruction is a combination of the polyp and the contrast material, while the colonoscopic image (inset) shows the lesion's true flat nature (arrowhead). <b>(d)</b> Axial 2D CT colonography image in another patient shows a polyp without a contrast material coat (arrowhead), which is much more difficult to see and is characterized by a subtle undulation. <b>(e)</b> Sagittal 2D reconstruction better shows the lesion (arrowhead). <b>(f)</b> Colonoscopic image confirms the lesion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170110&amp;id=fig3d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170110/asset/images/large/rg.2018170110.fig3e.jpeg" height="1558" width="1582" aria-labelledby="fig3e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3e</span>. Lesional contrast material coat of SSP at screening CT colonography. <b>(a, b)</b> Supine <b>(a)</b> and prone <b>(b)</b> axial two-dimensional (2D) CT colonography images show adherent contrast material (arrowheads), which aids in detection. Note how the contrast material outlines the lesion but not the normal colonic mucosa (magnified inset). <b>(c)</b> Three-dimensional (3D) endoluminal view shows that this flat lesion is more obvious and appears sessile, as the reconstruction is a combination of the polyp and the contrast material, while the colonoscopic image (inset) shows the lesion's true flat nature (arrowhead). <b>(d)</b> Axial 2D CT colonography image in another patient shows a polyp without a contrast material coat (arrowhead), which is much more difficult to see and is characterized by a subtle undulation. <b>(e)</b> Sagittal 2D reconstruction better shows the lesion (arrowhead). <b>(f)</b> Colonoscopic image confirms the lesion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170110&amp;id=fig3e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3f" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170110/asset/images/large/rg.2018170110.fig3f.jpeg" height="1558" width="1768" aria-labelledby="fig3f" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3f</span>. Lesional contrast material coat of SSP at screening CT colonography. <b>(a, b)</b> Supine <b>(a)</b> and prone <b>(b)</b> axial two-dimensional (2D) CT colonography images show adherent contrast material (arrowheads), which aids in detection. Note how the contrast material outlines the lesion but not the normal colonic mucosa (magnified inset). <b>(c)</b> Three-dimensional (3D) endoluminal view shows that this flat lesion is more obvious and appears sessile, as the reconstruction is a combination of the polyp and the contrast material, while the colonoscopic image (inset) shows the lesion's true flat nature (arrowhead). <b>(d)</b> Axial 2D CT colonography image in another patient shows a polyp without a contrast material coat (arrowhead), which is much more difficult to see and is characterized by a subtle undulation. <b>(e)</b> Sagittal 2D reconstruction better shows the lesion (arrowhead). <b>(f)</b> Colonoscopic image confirms the lesion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170110&amp;id=fig3f">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170110/asset/images/large/rg.2018170110.fig4a.jpeg" height="1448" width="1412" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span>. Typical SSP detected at CT colonography screening in a 67-year-old average-risk man. <b>(a, b)</b> Supine <b>(a)</b> and prone <b>(b)</b> axial 2D images show a representative lesion (arrowhead). The SSP is large, flat, and located in the ascending colon. Note the adherent film of contrast material on the lesion. <b>(c)</b> Three-dimensional image shows a more bulky-appearing lesion, an appearance created by the film of contrast material on the lesion at 2D CT colonography. <b>(d)</b> Colonoscopic image shows the subtle nature of the lesion (arrowheads). The overlying mucin and contrast material help detection here as well.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170110&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170110/asset/images/large/rg.2018170110.fig4b.jpeg" height="1448" width="1538" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span>. Typical SSP detected at CT colonography screening in a 67-year-old average-risk man. <b>(a, b)</b> Supine <b>(a)</b> and prone <b>(b)</b> axial 2D images show a representative lesion (arrowhead). The SSP is large, flat, and located in the ascending colon. Note the adherent film of contrast material on the lesion. <b>(c)</b> Three-dimensional image shows a more bulky-appearing lesion, an appearance created by the film of contrast material on the lesion at 2D CT colonography. <b>(d)</b> Colonoscopic image shows the subtle nature of the lesion (arrowheads). The overlying mucin and contrast material help detection here as well.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170110&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170110/asset/images/large/rg.2018170110.fig4c.jpeg" height="1164" width="1434" aria-labelledby="fig4c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4c</span>. Typical SSP detected at CT colonography screening in a 67-year-old average-risk man. <b>(a, b)</b> Supine <b>(a)</b> and prone <b>(b)</b> axial 2D images show a representative lesion (arrowhead). The SSP is large, flat, and located in the ascending colon. Note the adherent film of contrast material on the lesion. <b>(c)</b> Three-dimensional image shows a more bulky-appearing lesion, an appearance created by the film of contrast material on the lesion at 2D CT colonography. <b>(d)</b> Colonoscopic image shows the subtle nature of the lesion (arrowheads). The overlying mucin and contrast material help detection here as well.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170110&amp;id=fig4c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170110/asset/images/large/rg.2018170110.fig4d.jpeg" height="1164" width="1214" aria-labelledby="fig4d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4d</span>. Typical SSP detected at CT colonography screening in a 67-year-old average-risk man. <b>(a, b)</b> Supine <b>(a)</b> and prone <b>(b)</b> axial 2D images show a representative lesion (arrowhead). The SSP is large, flat, and located in the ascending colon. Note the adherent film of contrast material on the lesion. <b>(c)</b> Three-dimensional image shows a more bulky-appearing lesion, an appearance created by the film of contrast material on the lesion at 2D CT colonography. <b>(d)</b> Colonoscopic image shows the subtle nature of the lesion (arrowheads). The overlying mucin and contrast material help detection here as well.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170110&amp;id=fig4d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170110/asset/images/large/rg.2018170110.fig5a.jpeg" height="1269" width="1084" aria-labelledby="fig5a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span>. Detection at CT colonography from a 2D perspective. <b>(a)</b> Axial 2D CT colonography image shows a possible sessile polyp (arrowhead) and a haustral fold (arrow) in the ascending colon. <b>(b)</b> Three-dimensional endoluminal CT colonography image from the perspective of the arrowhead in <b>a</b> confirms the polypoid morphology of the suspected polyp on the 2D image. Red line = axial section level and orientation of the 2D image. <b>(c)</b> Three-dimensional CT colonography image from the perspective of the arrow in <b>a</b> confirms the suspected haustral fold. Red line = axial section level and orientation of the 2D image. The similarity of a fold to a polyp on a single 2D image makes the search pattern more difficult, requiring interactive scrolling to distinguish between the two.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170110&amp;id=fig5a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170110/asset/images/large/rg.2018170110.fig5b.jpeg" height="1269" width="1365" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span>. Detection at CT colonography from a 2D perspective. <b>(a)</b> Axial 2D CT colonography image shows a possible sessile polyp (arrowhead) and a haustral fold (arrow) in the ascending colon. <b>(b)</b> Three-dimensional endoluminal CT colonography image from the perspective of the arrowhead in <b>a</b> confirms the polypoid morphology of the suspected polyp on the 2D image. Red line = axial section level and orientation of the 2D image. <b>(c)</b> Three-dimensional CT colonography image from the perspective of the arrow in <b>a</b> confirms the suspected haustral fold. Red line = axial section level and orientation of the 2D image. The similarity of a fold to a polyp on a single 2D image makes the search pattern more difficult, requiring interactive scrolling to distinguish between the two.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170110&amp;id=fig5b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170110/asset/images/large/rg.2018170110.fig5c.jpeg" height="1269" width="1255" aria-labelledby="fig5c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5c</span>. Detection at CT colonography from a 2D perspective. <b>(a)</b> Axial 2D CT colonography image shows a possible sessile polyp (arrowhead) and a haustral fold (arrow) in the ascending colon. <b>(b)</b> Three-dimensional endoluminal CT colonography image from the perspective of the arrowhead in <b>a</b> confirms the polypoid morphology of the suspected polyp on the 2D image. Red line = axial section level and orientation of the 2D image. <b>(c)</b> Three-dimensional CT colonography image from the perspective of the arrow in <b>a</b> confirms the suspected haustral fold. Red line = axial section level and orientation of the 2D image. The similarity of a fold to a polyp on a single 2D image makes the search pattern more difficult, requiring interactive scrolling to distinguish between the two.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170110&amp;id=fig5c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170110/asset/images/large/rg.2018170110.fig6a.jpeg" height="987" width="1233" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span>. Detection from a 3D perspective. <b>(a)</b> Endoluminal view, the standard view that mirrors a colonoscopic view. <b>(b–d)</b> Other advanced 3D reconstructions include the band <b>(b)</b>, unfolded cube <b>(c)</b>, and perspective filet <b>(d)</b> views. These three views increase the amount of colonic surface visualized at a given time but at the expense of postprocessing artifact and distortion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170110&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170110/asset/images/large/rg.2018170110.fig6b.jpeg" height="987" width="1233" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span>. Detection from a 3D perspective. <b>(a)</b> Endoluminal view, the standard view that mirrors a colonoscopic view. <b>(b–d)</b> Other advanced 3D reconstructions include the band <b>(b)</b>, unfolded cube <b>(c)</b>, and perspective filet <b>(d)</b> views. These three views increase the amount of colonic surface visualized at a given time but at the expense of postprocessing artifact and distortion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170110&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170110/asset/images/large/rg.2018170110.fig6c.jpeg" height="1520" width="1900" aria-labelledby="fig6c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6c</span>. Detection from a 3D perspective. <b>(a)</b> Endoluminal view, the standard view that mirrors a colonoscopic view. <b>(b–d)</b> Other advanced 3D reconstructions include the band <b>(b)</b>, unfolded cube <b>(c)</b>, and perspective filet <b>(d)</b> views. These three views increase the amount of colonic surface visualized at a given time but at the expense of postprocessing artifact and distortion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170110&amp;id=fig6c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170110/asset/images/large/rg.2018170110.fig6d.jpeg" height="987" width="1233" aria-labelledby="fig6d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6d</span>. Detection from a 3D perspective. <b>(a)</b> Endoluminal view, the standard view that mirrors a colonoscopic view. <b>(b–d)</b> Other advanced 3D reconstructions include the band <b>(b)</b>, unfolded cube <b>(c)</b>, and perspective filet <b>(d)</b> views. These three views increase the amount of colonic surface visualized at a given time but at the expense of postprocessing artifact and distortion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170110&amp;id=fig6d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170110/asset/images/large/rg.2018170110.fig7a.jpeg" height="1122" width="1200" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span>. Confirmation of a suspected polyp. <b>(a, b)</b> Supine <b>(a)</b> and prone <b>(b)</b> axial 2D CT colonography images show that the suspected polyp (arrowhead) fulfills required criteria. The polyp remains fixed in location along the posterior rectal wall on both views. If it were stool, the polyp candidate should fall dependently to the anterior wall with prone imaging. Note the homogeneous attenuation on both views similar to that of adjacent muscle, signifying a soft-tissue nature. An adherent contrast material coat increases confidence in this candidate as a real lesion. <b>(c)</b> Three-dimensional endoluminal image shows sessile morphology. <b>(d)</b> Colonoscopic image confirms a lobulated polyp. Histologic analysis demonstrated an SSP. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r31" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r31">31</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170110&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170110/asset/images/large/rg.2018170110.fig7b.jpeg" height="1049" width="1190" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span>. Confirmation of a suspected polyp. <b>(a, b)</b> Supine <b>(a)</b> and prone <b>(b)</b> axial 2D CT colonography images show that the suspected polyp (arrowhead) fulfills required criteria. The polyp remains fixed in location along the posterior rectal wall on both views. If it were stool, the polyp candidate should fall dependently to the anterior wall with prone imaging. Note the homogeneous attenuation on both views similar to that of adjacent muscle, signifying a soft-tissue nature. An adherent contrast material coat increases confidence in this candidate as a real lesion. <b>(c)</b> Three-dimensional endoluminal image shows sessile morphology. <b>(d)</b> Colonoscopic image confirms a lobulated polyp. Histologic analysis demonstrated an SSP. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r31" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r31">31</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170110&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170110/asset/images/large/rg.2018170110.fig7c.jpeg" height="1049" width="1099" aria-labelledby="fig7c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7c</span>. Confirmation of a suspected polyp. <b>(a, b)</b> Supine <b>(a)</b> and prone <b>(b)</b> axial 2D CT colonography images show that the suspected polyp (arrowhead) fulfills required criteria. The polyp remains fixed in location along the posterior rectal wall on both views. If it were stool, the polyp candidate should fall dependently to the anterior wall with prone imaging. Note the homogeneous attenuation on both views similar to that of adjacent muscle, signifying a soft-tissue nature. An adherent contrast material coat increases confidence in this candidate as a real lesion. <b>(c)</b> Three-dimensional endoluminal image shows sessile morphology. <b>(d)</b> Colonoscopic image confirms a lobulated polyp. Histologic analysis demonstrated an SSP. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r31" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r31">31</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170110&amp;id=fig7c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170110/asset/images/large/rg.2018170110.fig7d.jpeg" height="1049" width="1414" aria-labelledby="fig7d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7d</span>. Confirmation of a suspected polyp. <b>(a, b)</b> Supine <b>(a)</b> and prone <b>(b)</b> axial 2D CT colonography images show that the suspected polyp (arrowhead) fulfills required criteria. The polyp remains fixed in location along the posterior rectal wall on both views. If it were stool, the polyp candidate should fall dependently to the anterior wall with prone imaging. Note the homogeneous attenuation on both views similar to that of adjacent muscle, signifying a soft-tissue nature. An adherent contrast material coat increases confidence in this candidate as a real lesion. <b>(c)</b> Three-dimensional endoluminal image shows sessile morphology. <b>(d)</b> Colonoscopic image confirms a lobulated polyp. Histologic analysis demonstrated an SSP. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r31" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r31">31</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170110&amp;id=fig7d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170110/asset/images/large/rg.2018170110.fig8a.jpeg" height="1207" width="1575" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span>. Coated flat polyp versus tagged adherent stool. <b>(a, b)</b> Diagrams show a coated polyp <b>(a)</b> and a plaque of tagged stool <b>(b)</b>. For a true polyp, there is an advancing border of soft tissue undermining the plaque (red line), whereas the tagged stool extends to the mucosal surface of the colonic wall with a concave smooth border (yellow line). <b>(c, d)</b> Supine <b>(c)</b> and prone <b>(d)</b> axial 2D CT colonography images show a flat coated SSP (red circles) in the ascending colon. Note the soft tissue undermining the contrast material coat (magnified inset). <b>(e)</b> Colonoscopic image confirms the flat SSP. <b>(f)</b> Supine 2D CT colonography image in another patient shows that the advancing border of the flat polyp underneath the contrast material coat (red circles) may not appear soft tissue due to beam hardening (magnified inset). <b>(g)</b> Colonoscopic image shows the flat SSP. <b>(h)</b> CT colonography image in another patient shows stool, which has a smooth curving border with the mucosal surface of the colon. No undermining advancing border is seen.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170110&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170110/asset/images/large/rg.2018170110.fig8b.jpeg" height="1207" width="1568" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span>. Coated flat polyp versus tagged adherent stool. <b>(a, b)</b> Diagrams show a coated polyp <b>(a)</b> and a plaque of tagged stool <b>(b)</b>. For a true polyp, there is an advancing border of soft tissue undermining the plaque (red line), whereas the tagged stool extends to the mucosal surface of the colonic wall with a concave smooth border (yellow line). <b>(c, d)</b> Supine <b>(c)</b> and prone <b>(d)</b> axial 2D CT colonography images show a flat coated SSP (red circles) in the ascending colon. Note the soft tissue undermining the contrast material coat (magnified inset). <b>(e)</b> Colonoscopic image confirms the flat SSP. <b>(f)</b> Supine 2D CT colonography image in another patient shows that the advancing border of the flat polyp underneath the contrast material coat (red circles) may not appear soft tissue due to beam hardening (magnified inset). <b>(g)</b> Colonoscopic image shows the flat SSP. <b>(h)</b> CT colonography image in another patient shows stool, which has a smooth curving border with the mucosal surface of the colon. No undermining advancing border is seen.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170110&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170110/asset/images/large/rg.2018170110.fig8c.jpeg" height="1085" width="1656" aria-labelledby="fig8c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8c</span>. Coated flat polyp versus tagged adherent stool. <b>(a, b)</b> Diagrams show a coated polyp <b>(a)</b> and a plaque of tagged stool <b>(b)</b>. For a true polyp, there is an advancing border of soft tissue undermining the plaque (red line), whereas the tagged stool extends to the mucosal surface of the colonic wall with a concave smooth border (yellow line). <b>(c, d)</b> Supine <b>(c)</b> and prone <b>(d)</b> axial 2D CT colonography images show a flat coated SSP (red circles) in the ascending colon. Note the soft tissue undermining the contrast material coat (magnified inset). <b>(e)</b> Colonoscopic image confirms the flat SSP. <b>(f)</b> Supine 2D CT colonography image in another patient shows that the advancing border of the flat polyp underneath the contrast material coat (red circles) may not appear soft tissue due to beam hardening (magnified inset). <b>(g)</b> Colonoscopic image shows the flat SSP. <b>(h)</b> CT colonography image in another patient shows stool, which has a smooth curving border with the mucosal surface of the colon. No undermining advancing border is seen.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170110&amp;id=fig8c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170110/asset/images/large/rg.2018170110.fig8d.jpeg" height="1085" width="1494" aria-labelledby="fig8d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8d</span>. Coated flat polyp versus tagged adherent stool. <b>(a, b)</b> Diagrams show a coated polyp <b>(a)</b> and a plaque of tagged stool <b>(b)</b>. For a true polyp, there is an advancing border of soft tissue undermining the plaque (red line), whereas the tagged stool extends to the mucosal surface of the colonic wall with a concave smooth border (yellow line). <b>(c, d)</b> Supine <b>(c)</b> and prone <b>(d)</b> axial 2D CT colonography images show a flat coated SSP (red circles) in the ascending colon. Note the soft tissue undermining the contrast material coat (magnified inset). <b>(e)</b> Colonoscopic image confirms the flat SSP. <b>(f)</b> Supine 2D CT colonography image in another patient shows that the advancing border of the flat polyp underneath the contrast material coat (red circles) may not appear soft tissue due to beam hardening (magnified inset). <b>(g)</b> Colonoscopic image shows the flat SSP. <b>(h)</b> CT colonography image in another patient shows stool, which has a smooth curving border with the mucosal surface of the colon. No undermining advancing border is seen.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170110&amp;id=fig8d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170110/asset/images/large/rg.2018170110.fig8e.jpeg" height="1075" width="1559" aria-labelledby="fig8e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8e</span>. Coated flat polyp versus tagged adherent stool. <b>(a, b)</b> Diagrams show a coated polyp <b>(a)</b> and a plaque of tagged stool <b>(b)</b>. For a true polyp, there is an advancing border of soft tissue undermining the plaque (red line), whereas the tagged stool extends to the mucosal surface of the colonic wall with a concave smooth border (yellow line). <b>(c, d)</b> Supine <b>(c)</b> and prone <b>(d)</b> axial 2D CT colonography images show a flat coated SSP (red circles) in the ascending colon. Note the soft tissue undermining the contrast material coat (magnified inset). <b>(e)</b> Colonoscopic image confirms the flat SSP. <b>(f)</b> Supine 2D CT colonography image in another patient shows that the advancing border of the flat polyp underneath the contrast material coat (red circles) may not appear soft tissue due to beam hardening (magnified inset). <b>(g)</b> Colonoscopic image shows the flat SSP. <b>(h)</b> CT colonography image in another patient shows stool, which has a smooth curving border with the mucosal surface of the colon. No undermining advancing border is seen.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170110&amp;id=fig8e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8f" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170110/asset/images/large/rg.2018170110.fig8f.jpeg" height="1075" width="1590" aria-labelledby="fig8f" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8f</span>. Coated flat polyp versus tagged adherent stool. <b>(a, b)</b> Diagrams show a coated polyp <b>(a)</b> and a plaque of tagged stool <b>(b)</b>. For a true polyp, there is an advancing border of soft tissue undermining the plaque (red line), whereas the tagged stool extends to the mucosal surface of the colonic wall with a concave smooth border (yellow line). <b>(c, d)</b> Supine <b>(c)</b> and prone <b>(d)</b> axial 2D CT colonography images show a flat coated SSP (red circles) in the ascending colon. Note the soft tissue undermining the contrast material coat (magnified inset). <b>(e)</b> Colonoscopic image confirms the flat SSP. <b>(f)</b> Supine 2D CT colonography image in another patient shows that the advancing border of the flat polyp underneath the contrast material coat (red circles) may not appear soft tissue due to beam hardening (magnified inset). <b>(g)</b> Colonoscopic image shows the flat SSP. <b>(h)</b> CT colonography image in another patient shows stool, which has a smooth curving border with the mucosal surface of the colon. No undermining advancing border is seen.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170110&amp;id=fig8f">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8g" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170110/asset/images/large/rg.2018170110.fig8g.jpeg" height="994" width="1393" aria-labelledby="fig8g" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8g</span>. Coated flat polyp versus tagged adherent stool. <b>(a, b)</b> Diagrams show a coated polyp <b>(a)</b> and a plaque of tagged stool <b>(b)</b>. For a true polyp, there is an advancing border of soft tissue undermining the plaque (red line), whereas the tagged stool extends to the mucosal surface of the colonic wall with a concave smooth border (yellow line). <b>(c, d)</b> Supine <b>(c)</b> and prone <b>(d)</b> axial 2D CT colonography images show a flat coated SSP (red circles) in the ascending colon. Note the soft tissue undermining the contrast material coat (magnified inset). <b>(e)</b> Colonoscopic image confirms the flat SSP. <b>(f)</b> Supine 2D CT colonography image in another patient shows that the advancing border of the flat polyp underneath the contrast material coat (red circles) may not appear soft tissue due to beam hardening (magnified inset). <b>(g)</b> Colonoscopic image shows the flat SSP. <b>(h)</b> CT colonography image in another patient shows stool, which has a smooth curving border with the mucosal surface of the colon. No undermining advancing border is seen.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170110&amp;id=fig8g">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8h" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170110/asset/images/large/rg.2018170110.fig8h.jpeg" height="994" width="1256" aria-labelledby="fig8h" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8h</span>. Coated flat polyp versus tagged adherent stool. <b>(a, b)</b> Diagrams show a coated polyp <b>(a)</b> and a plaque of tagged stool <b>(b)</b>. For a true polyp, there is an advancing border of soft tissue undermining the plaque (red line), whereas the tagged stool extends to the mucosal surface of the colonic wall with a concave smooth border (yellow line). <b>(c, d)</b> Supine <b>(c)</b> and prone <b>(d)</b> axial 2D CT colonography images show a flat coated SSP (red circles) in the ascending colon. Note the soft tissue undermining the contrast material coat (magnified inset). <b>(e)</b> Colonoscopic image confirms the flat SSP. <b>(f)</b> Supine 2D CT colonography image in another patient shows that the advancing border of the flat polyp underneath the contrast material coat (red circles) may not appear soft tissue due to beam hardening (magnified inset). <b>(g)</b> Colonoscopic image shows the flat SSP. <b>(h)</b> CT colonography image in another patient shows stool, which has a smooth curving border with the mucosal surface of the colon. No undermining advancing border is seen.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170110&amp;id=fig8h">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170110/asset/images/large/rg.2018170110.fig9a.jpeg" height="1517" width="1100" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span>. Apparent movement of a polyp due to the underlying colon. <b>(a)</b> Three-dimensional volume map shows an elongated tortuous sigmoid colon. <b>(b)</b> Supine and prone 2D CT colonography images show the shifting position of the sigmoid colon due to its mesentery. Note the difficulty in determining that the polyp (arrowheads) remains in the same position between supine and prone positioning. Without strong cross-sectional imaging skills, it may appear that the polyp candidate is falling to a dependent position on the prone image, and it may be incorrectly characterized as stool as opposed to the true cause, which is that the sigmoid colon has shifted and rotated in position. <b>(c)</b> The position of the polyp (arrowheads) is more apparent on coronal images.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170110&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170110/asset/images/large/rg.2018170110.fig9b.jpeg" height="1209" width="1718" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span>. Apparent movement of a polyp due to the underlying colon. <b>(a)</b> Three-dimensional volume map shows an elongated tortuous sigmoid colon. <b>(b)</b> Supine and prone 2D CT colonography images show the shifting position of the sigmoid colon due to its mesentery. Note the difficulty in determining that the polyp (arrowheads) remains in the same position between supine and prone positioning. Without strong cross-sectional imaging skills, it may appear that the polyp candidate is falling to a dependent position on the prone image, and it may be incorrectly characterized as stool as opposed to the true cause, which is that the sigmoid colon has shifted and rotated in position. <b>(c)</b> The position of the polyp (arrowheads) is more apparent on coronal images.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170110&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170110/asset/images/large/rg.2018170110.fig9c.jpeg" height="1209" width="2034" aria-labelledby="fig9c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9c</span>. Apparent movement of a polyp due to the underlying colon. <b>(a)</b> Three-dimensional volume map shows an elongated tortuous sigmoid colon. <b>(b)</b> Supine and prone 2D CT colonography images show the shifting position of the sigmoid colon due to its mesentery. Note the difficulty in determining that the polyp (arrowheads) remains in the same position between supine and prone positioning. Without strong cross-sectional imaging skills, it may appear that the polyp candidate is falling to a dependent position on the prone image, and it may be incorrectly characterized as stool as opposed to the true cause, which is that the sigmoid colon has shifted and rotated in position. <b>(c)</b> The position of the polyp (arrowheads) is more apparent on coronal images.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170110&amp;id=fig9c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170110/asset/images/large/rg.2018170110.fig10a.jpeg" height="949" width="1576" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span>. Cecal rotation pitfall. <b>(a)</b> Diagram shows the characteristic counterclockwise rotation of the cecum between supine and prone positioning. Note the relationship of the coated polyp to the appendiceal orifice, which is unchanged, confirming a fixed location on the colonic wall. <b>(b, c)</b> Supine <b>(b)</b> and prone <b>(c)</b> axial 2D CT colonography images in a patient with a coated SSP in the cecum show this phenomenon. Again, note the fixed relationship between the coated polyp (arrowhead) and the appendiceal orifice (arrow). <b>(d)</b> Colonoscopic image confirms an SSP ringed by mucin. (Fig 10d reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r25" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r25">25</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170110&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170110/asset/images/large/rg.2018170110.fig10b.jpeg" height="1299" width="1569" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span>. Cecal rotation pitfall. <b>(a)</b> Diagram shows the characteristic counterclockwise rotation of the cecum between supine and prone positioning. Note the relationship of the coated polyp to the appendiceal orifice, which is unchanged, confirming a fixed location on the colonic wall. <b>(b, c)</b> Supine <b>(b)</b> and prone <b>(c)</b> axial 2D CT colonography images in a patient with a coated SSP in the cecum show this phenomenon. Again, note the fixed relationship between the coated polyp (arrowhead) and the appendiceal orifice (arrow). <b>(d)</b> Colonoscopic image confirms an SSP ringed by mucin. (Fig 10d reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r25" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r25">25</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170110&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170110/asset/images/large/rg.2018170110.fig10c.jpeg" height="1476" width="1575" aria-labelledby="fig10c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10c</span>. Cecal rotation pitfall. <b>(a)</b> Diagram shows the characteristic counterclockwise rotation of the cecum between supine and prone positioning. Note the relationship of the coated polyp to the appendiceal orifice, which is unchanged, confirming a fixed location on the colonic wall. <b>(b, c)</b> Supine <b>(b)</b> and prone <b>(c)</b> axial 2D CT colonography images in a patient with a coated SSP in the cecum show this phenomenon. Again, note the fixed relationship between the coated polyp (arrowhead) and the appendiceal orifice (arrow). <b>(d)</b> Colonoscopic image confirms an SSP ringed by mucin. (Fig 10d reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r25" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r25">25</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170110&amp;id=fig10c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170110/asset/images/large/rg.2018170110.fig10d.jpeg" height="1126" width="1575" aria-labelledby="fig10d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10d</span>. Cecal rotation pitfall. <b>(a)</b> Diagram shows the characteristic counterclockwise rotation of the cecum between supine and prone positioning. Note the relationship of the coated polyp to the appendiceal orifice, which is unchanged, confirming a fixed location on the colonic wall. <b>(b, c)</b> Supine <b>(b)</b> and prone <b>(c)</b> axial 2D CT colonography images in a patient with a coated SSP in the cecum show this phenomenon. Again, note the fixed relationship between the coated polyp (arrowhead) and the appendiceal orifice (arrow). <b>(d)</b> Colonoscopic image confirms an SSP ringed by mucin. (Fig 10d reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r25" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r25">25</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170110&amp;id=fig10d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170110/asset/images/large/rg.2018170110.fig11a.jpeg" height="1301" width="1272" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span>. Apparent polyp movement on fold. <b>(a, b)</b> Supine <b>(a)</b> and prone <b>(b)</b> axial 2D CT colonography images show a change in position of a polyp (arrowhead) in relation to a haustral fold. The polyp projects off the fold on the supine image and resides in the crook between the fold and colonic wall on the prone image. This is a characteristic occurrence, presumably due to some redundancy in the mucosa in relation to the fold. It is important not to erroneously conclude movement related to sliding tagged stool. <b>(c)</b> Colonoscopic image confirms a polyp with mucin, which was an SSP at histologic analysis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170110&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170110/asset/images/large/rg.2018170110.fig11b.jpeg" height="1301" width="1177" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span>. Apparent polyp movement on fold. <b>(a, b)</b> Supine <b>(a)</b> and prone <b>(b)</b> axial 2D CT colonography images show a change in position of a polyp (arrowhead) in relation to a haustral fold. The polyp projects off the fold on the supine image and resides in the crook between the fold and colonic wall on the prone image. This is a characteristic occurrence, presumably due to some redundancy in the mucosa in relation to the fold. It is important not to erroneously conclude movement related to sliding tagged stool. <b>(c)</b> Colonoscopic image confirms a polyp with mucin, which was an SSP at histologic analysis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170110&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170110/asset/images/large/rg.2018170110.fig11c.jpeg" height="926" width="1252" aria-labelledby="fig11c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11c</span>. Apparent polyp movement on fold. <b>(a, b)</b> Supine <b>(a)</b> and prone <b>(b)</b> axial 2D CT colonography images show a change in position of a polyp (arrowhead) in relation to a haustral fold. The polyp projects off the fold on the supine image and resides in the crook between the fold and colonic wall on the prone image. This is a characteristic occurrence, presumably due to some redundancy in the mucosa in relation to the fold. It is important not to erroneously conclude movement related to sliding tagged stool. <b>(c)</b> Colonoscopic image confirms a polyp with mucin, which was an SSP at histologic analysis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170110&amp;id=fig11c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170110/asset/images/large/rg.2018170110.fig12a.jpeg" height="1200" width="1130" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span>. Retained tagged stool. <b>(a, b)</b> Supine axial 2D CT colonography image <b>(a)</b> and 3D CT colonography endoluminal view <b>(b)</b> show poor cleansing with retained right-sided tagged stool. Note how this would decrease the ability to detect contrast material plaques and thus coated polyps. <b>(c)</b> Axial 2D CT colonography image in another patient who reversed the order of the tagging agents shows a smooth adherent outline of the normal colonic mucosa.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170110&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170110/asset/images/large/rg.2018170110.fig12b.jpeg" height="1200" width="1347" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span>. Retained tagged stool. <b>(a, b)</b> Supine axial 2D CT colonography image <b>(a)</b> and 3D CT colonography endoluminal view <b>(b)</b> show poor cleansing with retained right-sided tagged stool. Note how this would decrease the ability to detect contrast material plaques and thus coated polyps. <b>(c)</b> Axial 2D CT colonography image in another patient who reversed the order of the tagging agents shows a smooth adherent outline of the normal colonic mucosa.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170110&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170110/asset/images/large/rg.2018170110.fig12c.jpeg" height="1200" width="1222" aria-labelledby="fig12c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12c</span>. Retained tagged stool. <b>(a, b)</b> Supine axial 2D CT colonography image <b>(a)</b> and 3D CT colonography endoluminal view <b>(b)</b> show poor cleansing with retained right-sided tagged stool. Note how this would decrease the ability to detect contrast material plaques and thus coated polyps. <b>(c)</b> Axial 2D CT colonography image in another patient who reversed the order of the tagging agents shows a smooth adherent outline of the normal colonic mucosa.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170110&amp;id=fig12c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170110/asset/images/large/rg.2018170110.fig13a.jpeg" height="1246" width="1375" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span>. Large TSA in a 56-year-old woman. The lesion was detected with CT colonography in the right colon. <b>(a, b)</b> Supine <b>(a)</b> and prone <b>(b)</b> axial 2D CT colonography images show a large soft-tissue polyp with elongated frond-like projections. Note the contrast material filling the numerous interstices. <b>(c)</b> Three-dimensional endoluminal CT colonography image shows a large lobulated lesion. <b>(d)</b> Colonoscopic image confirms the TSA. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r25" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r25">25</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170110&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170110/asset/images/large/rg.2018170110.fig13b.jpeg" height="1246" width="1272" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span>. Large TSA in a 56-year-old woman. The lesion was detected with CT colonography in the right colon. <b>(a, b)</b> Supine <b>(a)</b> and prone <b>(b)</b> axial 2D CT colonography images show a large soft-tissue polyp with elongated frond-like projections. Note the contrast material filling the numerous interstices. <b>(c)</b> Three-dimensional endoluminal CT colonography image shows a large lobulated lesion. <b>(d)</b> Colonoscopic image confirms the TSA. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r25" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r25">25</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170110&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170110/asset/images/large/rg.2018170110.fig13c.jpeg" height="1116" width="1144" aria-labelledby="fig13c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13c</span>. Large TSA in a 56-year-old woman. The lesion was detected with CT colonography in the right colon. <b>(a, b)</b> Supine <b>(a)</b> and prone <b>(b)</b> axial 2D CT colonography images show a large soft-tissue polyp with elongated frond-like projections. Note the contrast material filling the numerous interstices. <b>(c)</b> Three-dimensional endoluminal CT colonography image shows a large lobulated lesion. <b>(d)</b> Colonoscopic image confirms the TSA. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r25" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r25">25</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170110&amp;id=fig13c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13d" class="graphic"><im